  "prompt": "Can I apply for a PR in Australia while I am studying in Australia for a masters course on a student visa 573? I have met the criteria of 65 points.",
  "response": "Yes, you can apply for Permanent Residency (PR) in Australia while you are studying as long as you meet the eligibility criteria for one of the PR visa subclasses. The fact that you are on a student visa (subclass 573) does not prevent you from applying for PR. \n\nHere are a few options for PR that you might consider:\n\n1. **Subclass 189 - Skilled Independent Visa**: This is a points-based visa for skilled workers who are not sponsored by an employer, a state or territory, or a family member. If you meet the points requirement and satisfy other eligibility criteria (such as age, English language proficiency, nominated occupation, skills assessment, and health and character requirements), you can lodge an Expression of Interest (EOI) through SkillSelect.\n\n2. **Subclass 190 - Skilled Nominated Visa**: Similar to the 189 visa but you need to be nominated by an Australian state or territory government agency. You must express your interest through SkillSelect, and if you receive a nomination, you can then apply for PR.\n\n3. **Subclass 491 - Skilled Work Regional (Provisional) Visa**: A temporary visa for skilled workers who want to live and work in regional Australia. This visa can lead to PR after three years if you meet the requirements for the Subclass 191 visa.\n\nSince you mentioned you have met the criteria of 65 points, it suggests that you may be eligible under the points-tested system. However, keep in mind that the points threshold can change, and meeting the minimum criteria does not guarantee an invitation to apply, as invitations are issued based on the points ranking and demand for specific occupations.\n\nBefore applying, consider speaking with a migration agent to ensure that you understand all requirements and have the best chance of success. Additionally, always check the latest information and guidelines from the Department of Home Affairs, as immigration rules and procedures can change.",
